The proof uses induction on the structure of the derivation tree. The base case is when the derivation tree is a single node (the root). In this case, the number of leaves is 1, and the length of the result word is also 1. The inductive step considers the case where the root has multiple children. The total number of leaves in the main tree is the sum of the number of leaves in each of the child trees. The total length of the result word is the sum of the lengths of the result words from each of the child derivations. The induction hypothesis is that each child tree satisfies the property. The proof combines these facts to show that the main tree also satisfies the property.
